docs.abstract: President Trump, who has refused to release his tax returns, will file his 2017 tax return by October, according to the White House.
docs.snippet: President Trump, who has refused to release his tax returns, will file his 2017 tax return by October, according to the White House.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For decades, presidents have publicly released their tax returns each year — an act of transparency and a way to connect and commiserate with Americans on Tax Day.

headline.main: Trump Requests Extension to File 2017 Taxes
headline.print_headline: Unlike Presidents Before Him, Trump Asks for More Time to File His Taxes

byline.original: By Alan Rappeport and Michael D. Shear

docs.abstract: Emmet Flood’s hiring reflects concern that the Russia investigation will drag on and that the midterm elections could result in a Congress eager to take on the White House.
docs.snippet: Emmet Flood’s hiring reflects concern that the Russia investigation will drag on and that the midterm elections could result in a Congress eager to take on the White House.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump hired on Wednesday a Washington lawyer who represented Bill Clinton during his impeachment, a sign that the White House sees no immediate end to its legal problems and is girding for a combative relationship with a new Congress after the midterm elections.

headline.main: Trump Adds Clinton Impeachment Lawyer, Bracing for a Fight on Multiple Fronts
headline.print_headline: Trump Digs In, Adding Lawyer With Impeachment Experience

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court heard arguments on Tuesday in a long-running dispute over congressional and state legislative districts in Texas that challengers said discriminate against minority voters.

headline.main: Supreme Court Weighs Claims That Texas Voting Maps Discriminate Against Minorities
headline.print_headline: Justices Weigh Texas Case Of a Gerrymandered Map

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department inspector general delivered to Congress on Friday a scathing report that accused Andrew G. docs.abstract: The statement appeared to undercut an argument that Solicitor General Noel J. Francisco made before the Supreme Court, one that the Justice Department now says included a factual error.
docs.snippet: The statement appeared to undercut an argument that Solicitor General Noel J. Francisco made before the Supreme Court, one that the Justice Department now says included a factual error.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said on Monday that he would not apologize for campaign statements calling for a “Muslim ban,” appearing to undercut an assertion at a Supreme Court argument last week from Solicitor General Noel J. Francisco. In defending Mr. Trump’s efforts to restrict travel from several predominantly Muslim countries, Mr. Francisco said that the president had already disavowed the statements.

headline.main: ‘There’s No Reason to Apologize’ for Muslim Ban Remarks, Trump Says
headline.print_headline: President Says He Won’t Apologize For His Remarks Over ‘Muslim Ban’

docs.abstract: Nikki Haley, the ambassador to the United Nations, said Russian companies that have supported Syria’s chemical weapons would be targeted on Monday.
docs.snippet: Nikki Haley, the ambassador to the United Nations, said Russian companies that have supported Syria’s chemical weapons would be targeted on Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration plans to impose new sanctions against Russia on Monday to punish it for enabling the Syrian government’s use of chemical weapons in its civil war, the latest in a series of actions by both sides underscoring the deterioration in relations between Moscow and the West.

headline.main: Trump to Impose New Sanctions on Russia Over Support for Syria
headline.print_headline: Trump to Punish  Russia for Aiding  Attack by Syria

docs.abstract: A day after President Trump promised to slash red tape involved in weapons sales, the administration announced new policies, but experts said they would do little to speed exports.
docs.snippet: A day after President Trump promised to slash red tape involved in weapons sales, the administration announced new policies, but experts said they would do little to speed exports.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A day after President Trump promised to slash the red tape involved in weapons sales, the administration announced on Thursday a new policy that could vastly expand sales of armed drones, a contentious emblem of the shift toward remotely controlled warfare.

headline.main: Trump Administration Seeks to Expand Sales of Armed Drones
headline.print_headline: Trump Moves to Speed Up Weapons Sales and Expand Market for Armed Drones

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate voted on Wednesday to overturn an Obama-era rule that restricted automobile lenders from discriminating against minorities by charging them higher fees for car loans, in the latest attempt by Republican lawmakers to roll back financial regulations.

headline.print_headline: Senate Moves to Ease Rules Against Loan Bias

docs.abstract: In his first interview following Barbara Bush’s death, George W. Bush, the 43rd president, remembered his mother’s personal warmth and biting wit.
docs.snippet: In his first interview following Barbara Bush’s death, George W. Bush, the 43rd president, remembered his mother’s personal warmth and biting wit.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Even in the final days of her life, Barbara Bush retained the sharp tongue that belied her grandmotherly image. When her eldest son, former President George W. Bush, visited about 10 days before her death, the two playfully needled each other in the way they always did.

headline.main: In Barbara Bush’s Final Days, Faith, Courage and a Little Last Needling
headline.print_headline: Final Days Full of Faith, Courage and a Little Needling
